useCallback memoizes a function reference so it doesn't change between renders:

const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
  doSomething(id);
}, [id]);

Use when:
• Passing callbacks to memoized child components (React.memo)
• Callback is a dependency of useEffect
• Callback is used in a context provider value

DON'T use for every function — the memoization itself has a cost. Only use when preventing re-renders of expensive children or breaking effect dependency loops.

React.memo is a HOC that memoizes a component — it only re-renders if props change (shallow comparison).

const ExpensiveList = React.memo(function List({ items }) {
  return items.map(item => <Item key={item.id} {...item} />);
});

Use when:
• Component renders often with the same props
• Component is expensive to render
• Parent re-renders frequently but child props don't change

Don't use blindly — shallow comparison has a cost. Profile first to confirm a render bottleneck exists.

A custom hook is a function starting with 'use' that composes other hooks:

function useLocalStorage(key, initial) {
  const [value, setValue] = useState(() => {
    const stored = localStorage.getItem(key);
    return stored ? JSON.parse(stored) : initial;
  });
  useEffect(() => {
    localStorage.setItem(key, JSON.stringify(value));
  }, [key, value]);
  return [value, setValue];
}

Rules of Hooks:
1. Only call hooks at the top level (not inside loops/conditions)
2. Only call hooks from React functions (components or custom hooks)

useReducer manages state with a reducer function (like Redux):

const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(reducer, initialState);

function reducer(state, action) {
  switch (action.type) {
    case 'increment': return { count: state.count + 1 };
    default: return state;
  }
}

Prefer useReducer when:
• State logic is complex (multiple sub-values)
• Next state depends on previous state
• You want to centralize update logic
• Multiple actions affect the same state
• You need to pass dispatch down (stable reference, unlike setState closures)

A render prop is a function prop that returns React elements, letting a component share its internal logic:

<Mouse render={({ x, y }) => (
  <Cursor position={{ x, y }} />
)}/>

class Mouse extends React.Component {
  state = { x: 0, y: 0 };
  render() {
    return this.props.render(this.state);
  }
}

Mostly replaced by custom hooks in modern React, but still useful in libraries and when you need to share behavior between class and function components.

React batches multiple state updates into a single re-render for performance.

React 18+ automatic batching:
• ALL state updates are batched — in event handlers, timeouts, promises, native events
• setState calls in the same event are grouped into one render

function handleClick() {
  setCount(c => c + 1);  // doesn't re-render yet
  setFlag(f => !f);       // doesn't re-render yet
  // React re-renders ONCE with both updates
}

To opt out: flushSync(() => setState(val)) forces immediate render (rarely needed).
